<br>
Are there aspects of satanic philosophy that are keyed toward benefitting society rather than the individual?<br>
<br>
For the sake of this question let's avoid the &quot;what do you mean by 'good'&quot; ambiguity.  Just use common social definitions of the term.  As an aside, I wouldn't consider aggressive behavior 'evil,' though it can lead to evil.  It's just sometimes -- as you say earlier in the paragraph -- &quot;needed.&quot;<br>
<br>
I'm just interested in whether satanism can inherently produce behaviors which the average person could clearly construe as good toward society as a whole.  After that we can discuss whether acts that are good solely for an individual warrant being considered good acts in any way. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
